Step 1: Create the Configuration File
First, create the blueprint for your checklist.
Create a new file in src/features/warehousing/config/. Name it something descriptive, for example, pestControlChecklist.js.
Add the checklist structure based on the following template:
javascript


/**
* @type {import('../../checklists/components/ChecklistEngine').ChecklistConfig}
*/


export const myNewChecklistConfig = {
   // MUST be unique, strictly lowercase with no spaces (e.g., 'pest-control')
   id: 'my-new-checklist-id',
   title: 'Pest Control Checklist',
   description: 'Weekly inspection of all warehouse sectors',
  
   // Optional: Define location constraints for specific sections
   // locationCheckpoints: {
   //     'section-id': 'location-key-from-locations-js'
   // },
   sections: [
       {
           id: 'section-1-id',
           title: 'Part 1: Exterior Inspection',
           icon: '🏢', // Any emoji works
           description: 'Check perimeter for access points',
           estimatedDuration: 15, // minutes
           requiresLocation: true, // Forces GPS check
           fields: [
               {
                   id: 'perimeter-check',
                   type: 'checkbox',
                   label: 'Perimeter checked for gaps',
                   required: true
               },
               {
                   id: 'notes',
                   type: 'text',
                   label: 'Observations',
                   placeholder: 'Enter details...'
               }
           ]
       },
       {
           id: 'section-2-id',
           title: 'Part 2: Interior Traps',
           icon: '🪤',
           fields: [
               {
                   id: 'trap-log',
                   type: 'log-table',
                   label: 'Trap Inspection Log',
                   columns: [
                       { key: 'trapId', label: 'Trap ID', type: 'text' },
                       { key: 'status', label: 'Status', type: 'select', options: [{ value: 'Caught', label: 'Caught' }, { value: 'Empty', label: 'Empty' }] }
                   ]
               }
           ]
       }
   ]
};
TIP
Available Field Types:
text: Single-line text input
number: Numeric input
checkbox: Simple Yes/No toggle
select: Dropdown menu (requires options: [{value: 'x', label: 'X'}] structure)
date: interactive Date picker
time: Time picker
log-table: Dynamic table for adding multiple rows of data
summary: Automatic summary block (usually placed at the end of the form)
Step 2: Register the Checklist in the Supervisor App (TaskDetail.jsx)
The Supervisor app needs to know about this checklist to let staff fill it out.
Open src/pages/supervisor/TaskDetail.jsx.
Import your file at the top with the other checklist configurations:
javascript
import { myNewChecklistConfig } from '@/features/warehousing/config/pestControlChecklist';
Find the CHECKLIST_CONFIGS dictionary object and add your new ID:
javascript
const CHECKLIST_CONFIGS = {
 'milling': millingChecklistConfig,
 'briquette': briquetteChecklistConfig,
 // ... existing configs
 'my-new-checklist-id': myNewChecklistConfig, // <--- Add your config!
};
IMPORTANT
The dictionary key ('my-new-checklist-id') must exactly match the string used when the Manager assigns a new task.
Step 3: Enable Managers to View It (ManagerTaskDetail.jsx & LiveMonitoring.jsx)
The Manager portal needs to know how to render the live form progress. Since managers can review checklists dynamically as they happen:
Open src/pages/manager/ManagerTaskDetail.jsx.
Import your config alongside the others at the top:
javascript
import { myNewChecklistConfig as pestControlConfig } from '@/features/warehousing/config/pestControlChecklist';
Locate the switch (task.checklistType) block (around line 45) and add a case for your new checklist ID so the system passes the correct configuration to the reporting UI:
javascript
case 'my-new-checklist-id':
   config = pestControlConfig;
   break;
Repeat these exact steps 2 & 3 inside src/pages/manager/LiveMonitoring.jsx so the checklist format successfully displays over the "Live Monitor" panel.
Step 4: Add to Task Assignments (TaskManagement.jsx)
Finally, you need to allow Managers to create and assign instances of this new checklist.
Open src/pages/manager/TaskManagement.jsx.
Find the filter Dropdown (around line 240) and add your item:
javascript
<SelectItem value="my-new-checklist-id">Pest Control Checklist</SelectItem>
Under the "New Task" Dialog (around line 375), find the "Type" Select component and add your item so it can actually be assigned out:
javascript
<SelectItem value="my-new-checklist-id">Pest Control Checklist</SelectItem>
Find the onValueChange handler just above that select block (around line 358) and add a ternary/switch case to auto-fill the Task Name when the manager picks the type:
javascript
const autoName = val === 'milling' ? 'Milling Production Checklist'
              // ...existing logic...
              : val === 'my-new-checklist-id' ? 'Pest Control Checklist'
              : '';

Step 5: Test the Application!
You don't need to manually configure the database (Firebase handles schema dynamically using the tasks and submissions collections).
Log into the local application as a Manager.
Go to Manager Dashboard -> Task Management.
Click "New Assignment". You should see your new checklist type. Apply it to an active Supervisor account.
Log out, then log in using that specific Supervisor account.
Open up the newly assigned task on their UI and verify the checklist interface pops up correctly and displays the icons and form fields!

